.TH BDUMP 1 "July 2026" "User Manuals"

.SH NAME
bdump \- rizzed up remake of
.I od
,
.I hexdump
,
.I xxd
et al

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B bdump [-xodSHWBLbnsrlhV] [-s
.I n_bytes
.B ] [-r
.I n_bytes
.B ] [-l
.I n_bytes
.B ]
.I FILE|STDIN


.SH DESCRIPTION
.B bdump
prints unambiguous representations of individual bytes to STDOUT, or half-word and full-word (2 and 4 byte) groupings
given the appropriate options. It also prints a textual representation of bytes which fall into the range of
ascii-printable characters.
.PP
It takes a FILE name as argument, or reads from STDIN if FILE is not provided.
.PP
.B bdump
divides its output into four logically separate 'cells' using the unicode box-drawing glyphs.
At the top is a banner which (for now) just prints the name of
the file being dumped. Below the banner, the output is divided into three different cells. From L to R they are:
.PP
The
.I offset well.
This is a fixed-width cell that prints the beginning offset of each line in the format chosen by the
user. By default, this format is hexadecimal.
.PP
The
.I data dump
cell. This is the main cell where the bytes are printed in the radix format chosen by the user. This format is
unsigned hexadecimal by default, but can be changed to unsigned octal, unsigned decimal, signed decimal, or unsigned
binary using
command line flags. Note that changing the radix format will also change the format displayed in the offset well
EXCEPT for binary output, in which case the offset well will display the offsets in hexadecimal.
.PP
The
.I ascii dump
cell prints bytes which fall within the range of ascii-printable characters as those characters, else represents the
non-printable bytes as Unicode glyph \\x00B7 aka the middle dot.
.PP
The number of bytes written per line can be set using the
.I --line-width
argument. The default value is 16. Regardless of this value, each line will start with the offset of the first byte,
the bytes themselves in the chosen format, and the ascii representations (if representable) of the same bytes.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB-h or --help\fP
Print quick usage details to the screen.
.TP
\fB-V or --version\fP
Print version information to the screen.
.TP
\fB-x or --hex\fP
Format output in hexadecimal format. This is the default.
.TP
\fB-o or --oct\fP
Format output in octal format.
.TP
\fB-d or --unsigned\fP
Format output in unsigned decimal format.
.TP
\fB-S or --signed\fP
Format output in signed decimal format.
.TP
\fB-b or --bin\fP
Format output as binary bit-strings. Note that the offset will be displayed in hexadecimal, and that bitstring output
can only be grouped as single bytes. I'm not of the opinion that this option is in any way practically useful, but it may
be interesting to those trying to teach themselves to read binary.
.TP
\fB-H or --half-word\fP
Combine 2 bytes into half-word groupings.
.TP
\fB-W or --word\fP
Combine 4 bytes into full-word groupings.
.TP
\fB-L or --little-endian\fP
.TP
\fB-B or --big-endian\fP
Display half and full-word groupings in either little-endian or big-endian byte order. The default if neither of these
options is specified is to display using the byte order of the underlying machine.
.TP
\fB-n or --no-elide\fP
By default, 2+ lines of just zero bytes (NULLs) are elided, and replaced with a message which states how many lines
were elided. With this option, all of the zero-byte lines are printed.
.TP
\fB-lN or --line-width=N\fP
Display N bytes per row. This arg is hard-capped at 255, however, it is advised to not use much more than 48 depending
on the width of your terminal.
.TP
\fB-sN or --start-offset=N\fP
Start the dump N bytes into the input, ie: skip the first N bytes of the file.
.TP
\fB-rN or --read-size=N\fP
Stop dumping after N bytes. Note that this and the previous option can be combined to select arbitrary slices of the file.
.TP
.PP
.SH BUGS
.PP
The width of the offset well is fixed at 8 zero-padded chars no matter which radix is used to display it. This is not
really a practical problem, but keep in mind that the file-size limits for each of hex, dec, and oct is ~4GB, ~95MB, and
~16MB respectively. When dumping files larger than this the columns will become unaligned to accommodate the wider offset
display.
.PP
I probably can't be arsed to calculate the necessary offset well width based on file size dynamically, but I could add
a char or two to the fixed-width if enough people complain about it.
